{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cff788a1-bbb9-426b-8c18-48b42898ce07","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Action | Events fired |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| User switches away | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| User returns | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n| iOS background (state save) | `Backgrounding` (use `e.State` to persist data) |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` is iOS-only; on Android/Windows it won't fire. Use `Stopped` for cross-platform background detection.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8165ca87-f8a1-4f4b-b630-f890fcf5c61b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development — I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":440,"requestId":"B7D3:396FF8:130889:190CCF:69FFD7FD"},"id":"359d805b-1a94-46b8-8a92-38b293a5b5d6","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:57:42.312Z","parentId":"71197116-75e7-49e6-9f7b-c982d84ab4b0"}
